Colombian Privacy Addendum V1.0
Introductory Text
If you are using the Unmind platform and live in Colombia, then when we collect and use personal information about you, we are subject to Colombian privacy laws. These include Statutory Law 1266 of 2008 and its amendment, Law 2157 of 2021 alongside Law 1581 of 2012 and Decree 1377 of 2013 and Decree 866 of 2014. This means that we are responsible for protecting your personal information in compliance with these laws as well as with our own UK data protection legislation.
We ask that you make some time to read the additional information contained in this privacy addendum alongside our Global Privacy Policy so that you understand your rights and choices relating to your personal information as a resident of Colombia.
Our legal basis for processing
We describe our purposes, sharing practices and the categories of data we process in our Global Privacy Policy, you can read that
here
.
When collecting and processing your information for the purposes identified in our Global Privacy Policy, we do so with your explicit consent. This means that when you go to our sign-up page, we will require you to read our Global Privacy Policy and this addendum before reading our sign up statement and agreeing to it.
We will keep a copy of your consent with us for the entirety of the time you have an account with us and for three years from the end of your time with Unmind. This is to ensure that we can provide evidence of your consent for any future legal proceedings.
Can I withdraw my consent?
You can withdraw your consent at any time (unless you are withdrawing consent to avoid a legal or contractual obligation). All you have to do is let us know by emailing us at
privacy@unmind.com
.
Our Support Team will respond to your as soon as possible and make sure that your account is deleted and that we permanently and irrevocably anonymise your information per the
data security, integrity and retention section
of our Global Privacy Policy.
Your rights and choices
Colombian data protection legislation gives you the right to do the following:
To be informed:
We will always let you know when we are processing your information and our purpose for doing so. But if you have any questions, you can ask us at any time. You can also ask us to show you our policies that regulate the processing of your personal data.
Request access to your personal data:
You have the right to access your information (if we’re processing it) so that you can check we are processing it in alignment with Colombian legislation.
Request rectification of your personal data:
You have the right to ask us to update or correct the personal information that we hold about you if it is inaccurate, incomplete or out of date. We have designed our platform so that you can make these changes yourself, but you can contact us if you are having trouble.
Request that we delete your data:
You can ask us to delete or revoke any information we hold about you if the collection and processing of this information is not compliant with Colombian law. Please remember, we will only proceed with this once the SIC determines that Unmind is being non-compliant.
To object:
You can object to Unmind processing your information. But just like requests for deletion, we will only proceed with this once the SIC determines that Unmind is being non-compliant.
To request evidence of your consent:
You can request to see our record of your consent to our use and processing of your information at any time.
Lodging a complaint
If you feel that we have not processed your information according to the purpose we have stated in our Global Privacy Policy, or you have not been happy with the way we have responded to any of your requests about your information, then we encourage you to contact our Data Protection Officer at
privacy@unmind.com
. We will get back to you as soon as possible.
If you are still unhappy, you have the right to petition for the revocation or suppression of the personal data we hold about you to the Superintendency of Industry and Commerce (“SIC”).
Data Protection Officer
At Unmind, we take the protection of your personal information very seriously, so we have appointed a Data Protection Officer (DPO) to oversee our compliance with Colombian data protection laws. If you have any questions about this addendum or our Privacy Policy, then please contact our DPO at
privacy@unmind.com
. We will always ensure to respond to you in your preferred language (Spanish or English).
